Input: [100, 4, 200, 1, 3, 2]
Output: 4
Explanation: The sequence is [1, 2, 3, 4]

logic:
use set to remove the duplicate elements in the count
check the previous element exist as start of sequence to avoid duplicate count (if check the current one)
use the current element and start the count 
check next element exist then increase the count else break the loop and assign the count
then check other not exist element 



class Solution {

    // Function to return length of longest subsequence of consecutive integers.
    public int longestConsecutive(int[] arr) {
        // code here
        Set<Integer> set = new HashSet<>();

        int maxCount =0;
        for (int n: arr){
            set.add(n);
        }
        for(int s: set){
            if(!set.contains(s-1)){
                
            int currentNum =s;
            int count =1;
            
            while (set.contains(currentNum+1)){
                count++;
                currentNum++;
                
            }
            maxCount = Math.max(maxCount, count);
            }
        }
        return maxCount;
    }
}
